01:03:42.585 --> 01:03:44.108
God, yes. I want all of these.

1295
01:03:44.191 --> 01:03:45.769
MARY: Ah-ah. Just take one.

1296
01:03:45.852 --> 01:03:47.672
The rest is for
the Christmas party tonight.

1297
01:03:47.755 --> 01:03:49.575
What Christmas party?
There's a Christmas party?

1298
01:03:49.658 --> 01:03:51.577
MARY: Yeah, at Miss Crane's house.

1299
01:03:51.660 --> 01:03:53.150
I'm only going to go for a little bit.

1300
01:03:53.233 --> 01:03:54.778
Show my face and say I was there.

1301
01:03:54.861 --> 01:03:57.237
You know, Miss Crane said
she invited you too.

1302
01:03:58.306 --> 01:03:59.860
-I want to go to the party.
-(Paul stammers)

1303
01:03:59.943 --> 01:04:02.357
She didn't mean it.
We were just making small talk.

1304
01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:04.128
If you don't want to go, don't go.

1305
01:04:04.211 --> 01:04:05.624
-I'll take him.
-(Paul scoffs)

1306
01:04:05.707 --> 01:04:06.999
Mary can take me.

1307
01:04:07.082 --> 01:04:09.001
No, that's not how it works.

1308
01:04:09.084 --> 01:04:10.921
You're under my supervision.

1309
01:04:12.056 --> 01:04:14.006
Okay, maybe it's fine
for you to sit around here

1310
01:04:14.089 --> 01:04:15.876
and read books all day,

1311
01:04:15.959 --> 01:04:17.636
but I'm losing my goddamn mind.

1312
01:04:17.719 --> 01:04:19.341
-Jesus!
-MARY: Hey!

1313
01:04:19.424 --> 01:04:21.013
Watch your mouth, young man.

1314
01:04:21.096 --> 01:04:22.641
Not on Christmas Eve.

1315
01:04:22.724 --> 01:04:24.313
You see?

1316
01:04:24.396 --> 01:04:26.282
I can't trust him in a social situation.

1317
01:04:26.365 --> 01:04:28.152
Mr. Hunham, if you're too chickenshit

1318
01:04:28.235 --> 01:04:30.451
to go to this party, then just say that.

1319
01:04:30.534 --> 01:04:32.486
-But don't fuck it up for the little asshole.
-Mm.

1320
01:04:32.569 --> 01:04:34.978
What's wrong with you? It's just a party.

1321
01:04:36.476 --> 01:04:39.064
-What are you afraid of?
-(sighs) I don't know.

1322
01:04:39.147 --> 01:04:41.660
Shit. Now you got me nervous.

1323
01:04:41.743 --> 01:04:44.812
("White Christmas"
by The Swingle Singers playing)

1324
01:05:06.209 --> 01:05:08.275
♪ ♪

1325
01:05:23.886 --> 01:05:26.194
(sniffing)

1326
01:05:36.206 --> 01:05:38.668
-(spraying)
-Mm.

1327
01:05:41.002 --> 01:05:42.573
Yeah.

1328
01:05:50.055 --> 01:05:51.939
(lively chatter)

1329
01:05:52.022 --> 01:05:55.091
("Jingle Bells" by Herb Alpert
& The Tijuana Brass playing)

1330
01:06:02.496 --> 01:06:04.215
-Oh, hi.
-Oh, hi.

1331
01:06:04.298 --> 01:06:06.547
-Oh, you made it. Welcome.
-(chuckles) Yes.

1332
01:06:06.630 --> 01:06:08.714
Hi. Aw.

1333
01:06:08.797 --> 01:06:10.122
I am so glad you're here.

1334
01:06:10.205 --> 01:06:11.453
We're happy to be here.

1335
01:06:11.536 --> 01:06:12.960
Where should I put these?

1336
01:06:13.043 --> 01:06:14.654
Um, oh. (chuckles)

1337
01:06:14.737 --> 01:06:16.161
(gasps)

1338
01:06:16.244 --> 01:06:17.789
Those, I'll be putting
on my bedside table.

1339
01:06:17.872 --> 01:06:20.132
(laughing): Oh! You're a wicked woman.

1340
01:06:20.215 --> 01:06:22.299
-You have no idea.
-Oh!

1341
01:06:22.382 --> 01:06:24.235
Certainly a lot of people here.

1342
01:06:24.318 --> 01:06:26.171
(sighs) Yeah, yeah.

1343
01:06:26.254 --> 01:06:28.470
Some family, friends from town.

1344
01:06:28.553 --> 01:06:29.900
-Oh.
-Only you guys from work.

1345
01:06:29.983 --> 01:06:31.407
-Ah.
-Yeah.

1346
01:06:31.490 --> 01:06:33.805
-That's my mom on the couch.
-PAUL: Mm-hmm.

1347
01:06:33.888 --> 01:06:36.346
MISS CRANE: Uh, that's my sister Kathy

1348
01:06:36.429 --> 01:06:38.986
and her son Marvin.

1349
01:06:39.069 --> 01:06:41.648
Oh, and that's my friend Tom.

1350
01:06:41.731 --> 01:06:43.353
He owns the men's clothing store

1351
01:06:43.436 --> 01:06:44.783
-on Bolen Street.
-PAUL: Of course.

1352
01:06:44.866 --> 01:06:46.406
MISS CRANE: Yeah, and his son.

1353
01:06:49.741 --> 01:06:51.625
(chatter and music fade)

1354
01:06:51.708 --> 01:06:54.216
(music box playing "Away in a Manger")

1355
01:07:09.497 --> 01:07:10.809
MISS CRANE: Angus.

1356
01:07:10.892 --> 01:07:12.349
This is Angus Tully.

1357
01:07:12.432 --> 01:07:14.219
He's one of our students at Barton.

1358
01:07:14.302 --> 01:07:16.931
This is my niece Elise.

1359
01:07:17.934 --> 01:07:20.225
"Niece Elise." Nice.

1360
01:07:20.308 --> 01:07:22.062
MISS CRANE: And this is Mr. Hunham.

1361
01:07:22.145 --> 01:07:24.064
He's one of our finest teachers.

1362
01:07:24.147 --> 01:07:25.362
-PAUL: Oh.
-MISS CRANE: History, right?

1363
01:07:25.445 --> 01:07:26.726
PAUL: Uh, ancient civilizations.

1364
01:07:26.809 --> 01:07:27.958
MISS CRANE: Ah. (chuckles)

1365
01:07:28.041 --> 01:07:29.498
And this is Mary Lamb.

1366
01:07:29.581 --> 01:07:31.500
She is the manager of the cafeteria.

1367
01:07:31.583 --> 01:07:32.567
-ELISE: Cool.
-Hi.

1368
01:07:32.650 --> 01:07:33.997
Hi. (chuckles)

1369
01:07:34.080 --> 01:07:36.505
Um, hey, why don't you take Angus

1370
01:07:36.588 --> 01:07:38.507
down into the basement?

1371
01:07:38.590 --> 01:07:39.871
Introduce him to our family tradition.

1372
01:07:39.954 --> 01:07:41.576
Come on.

1373
01:07:41.659 --> 01:07:44.381
Okay, and, uh, why don't I
get you guys some drinks?

1374
01:07:44.464 --> 01:07:46.185
-Uh, Jim Beam for you, right?
-Correct.

1375
01:07:46.268 --> 01:07:47.549
Okay, and what about you, Mary?

1376
01:07:47.632 --> 01:07:49.650
-Uh, I'll take a whiskey.
-Okay.

1377
01:07:49.733 --> 01:07:51.487
(kids chattering)

1378
01:07:51.570 --> 01:07:53.390
♪ He's the jolly little fellow
called Santa Claus ♪

1379
01:07:53.473 --> 01:07:55.986
♪ Who'll be around
on Christmas Eve night ♪

1380
01:07:56.069 --> 01:07:58.725
♪ He's a chubby little fellow
with a long white beard ♪

1381
01:07:58.808 --> 01:08:00.727
♪ And he comes from far away... ♪

1382
01:08:00.810 --> 01:08:02.696
ANGUS: This is what you wanted to show me?

1383
01:08:02.779 --> 01:08:06.337
I grew up playing down here
during my aunt's parties.

1384
01:08:06.420 --> 01:08:08.240
I think it's kind of cool.

1385
01:08:08.323 --> 01:08:10.325
There's a purity to it.

1386
01:08:11.460 --> 01:08:14.906
I mean, every child is an artist.

1387
01:08:14.989 --> 01:08:18.844
The problem is remaining
an artist when we grow up.

1388
01:08:18.927 --> 01:08:20.681
Picasso said that.

1389
01:08:20.764 --> 01:08:22.452
Picasso's cool.

1390
01:08:22.535 --> 01:08:24.091
Yeah, I saw <i>Guernica</i> once.

1391
01:08:24.174 --> 01:08:25.884
-You know, the-the big mural?
-Yeah.

1392
01:08:25.967 --> 01:08:27.952
-With the horse?
-(laughs)

1393
01:08:28.035 --> 01:08:30.229
Yeah, I know <i>Guernica.</i> You really saw it?

1394
01:08:30.312 --> 01:08:33.397
Yeah. At The Museum
of Modern Art in New York.

1395
01:08:33.480 --> 01:08:35.564
It's huge.

1396
01:08:35.647 --> 01:08:37.863
My dad took me.

1397
01:08:37.946 --> 01:08:40.063
♪ Merry Christmas ♪

1398
01:08:40.146 --> 01:08:42.065
("Silent Night" by
The Temptations playing)

1399
01:08:42.148 --> 01:08:47.147
-♪ To each one of you ♪
-♪ To all of you ♪

1400
01:08:47.230 --> 01:08:50.216
-♪ Ooh-ooh ♪
-♪ Mm ♪

1401
01:08:50.299 --> 01:08:55.980
♪ Silent night ♪

1402
01:08:56.063 --> 01:08:59.951
♪ Holy night... ♪

1403
01:09:00.034 --> 01:09:02.102
There you go.

1404
01:09:03.677 --> 01:09:05.165
Hey, how you doing, hmm?

1405
01:09:05.248 --> 01:09:07.415
-I'm doing all right.
-Okay.

1406
01:09:08.946 --> 01:09:10.962
They put me in charge of the music.

1407
01:09:11.045 --> 01:09:12.667
Who put you in charge of the music?

1408
01:09:12.750 --> 01:09:13.899
I did.

1409
01:09:13.982 --> 01:09:15.670
-(both laugh)
-You so crazy.

1410
01:09:15.753 --> 01:09:17.804
Oh. I got you something.

1411
01:09:17.887 --> 01:09:20.312
-No, Danny.
-Yeah, go ahead.

1412
01:09:20.395 --> 01:09:22.072
Mm-mm. You didn't have to do all this.

1413
01:09:22.155 --> 01:09:25.075
I don't have to do anything
but pay taxes and die.

1414
01:09:25.158 --> 01:09:27.253
I wanted to. Here.

1415
01:09:27.336 --> 01:09:32.935
♪ Holy infant so tender and mild... ♪

1416
01:09:34.906 --> 01:09:36.427
This is lovely.

1417
01:09:36.510 --> 01:09:37.989
-Thank you.
-You're welcome.

1418
01:09:38.072 --> 01:09:39.496
But, Danny, I didn't get you anything.

1419
01:09:39.579 --> 01:09:40.794
Yes, you did.

1420
01:09:40.877 --> 01:09:43.665
You got me that beautiful smile.

1421
01:09:43.748 --> 01:09:45.469
(Danny chuckling)

1422
01:09:45.552 --> 01:09:47.273
-There it is.
-(Mary chuckles)

1423
01:09:47.356 --> 01:09:50.001
(laughing): There it is.

1424
01:09:50.084 --> 01:09:53.153
-Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas.

1425
01:09:54.332 --> 01:09:55.512
(kids chattering)

1426
01:09:55.595 --> 01:09:56.942
ANGUS: Am I doing this right?

1427
01:09:57.025 --> 01:09:58.928
ELISE: There's no right or wrong.

1428
01:09:59.997 --> 01:10:03.289
♪ I wish my mom would marry Santa Claus ♪

1429
01:10:03.372 --> 01:10:07.326
♪ Then I know he would always stay ♪

1430
01:10:07.409 --> 01:10:11.693
♪ And we could always play
with the toys... ♪

1431
01:10:11.776 --> 01:10:13.860
Are you trying to look down my shirt?

1432
01:10:13.943 --> 01:10:16.731
(laughs): No.

1433
01:10:16.814 --> 01:10:18.816
Yes.

1434
01:10:22.525 --> 01:10:24.211
You know, I'm not gonna do this

1435
01:10:24.294 --> 01:10:25.806
if you're not gonna take it seriously.

1436
01:10:25.889 --> 01:10:28.039
(laughing): I am taking it seriously.

1437
01:10:28.122 --> 01:10:30.074
As seriously as one can take
finger painting.

1438
01:10:30.157 --> 01:10:31.680
(laughing): You're not.

1439
01:10:31.763 --> 01:10:35.536
You missed this whole area right here.

1440
01:10:37.672 --> 01:10:41.019
♪ And it would always be ♪

1441
01:10:41.102 --> 01:10:45.172
♪ Like Christmas every day for me. ♪

1442
01:10:59.023 --> 01:11:00.495
(chuckles)

1443
01:11:01.498 --> 01:11:02.843
Oh. (chuckles)

1444
01:11:02.926 --> 01:11:04.713
-Well...
-Mistletoe. (laughs)

1445
01:11:04.796 --> 01:11:07.210
Oh, yes, of course,
that's-that's why. Right.

1446
01:11:07.293 --> 01:11:09.289
-Ah.
-(both laughing)

1447
01:11:09.372 --> 01:11:10.620
You know, it's interesting.

1448
01:11:10.703 --> 01:11:13.392
Aeneas, uh, carried mistletoe with him

1449
01:11:13.475 --> 01:11:15.262
when he descended into Hades, uh,

1450
01:11:15.345 --> 01:11:16.890
in search of his father.

1451
01:11:16.973 --> 01:11:18.975
Oh. Huh.

1452
01:11:20.044 --> 01:11:22.302
Anyway, uh, I like your tree.

1453
01:11:22.385 --> 01:11:24.194
It's very space-age.

1454
01:11:24.277 --> 01:11:27.065
Oh! I bought it to commemorate
the moon landing.

1455
01:11:27.148 --> 01:11:29.474
-Really? Oh. Oh.
-Yeah.

1456
01:11:29.557 --> 01:11:31.251
(Miss Crane sighs)

1457
01:11:32.892 --> 01:11:34.974
So, where's your family this Christmas?

1458
01:11:35.057 --> 01:11:36.811
Nowhere. I'm an only child.

1459
01:11:36.894 --> 01:11:38.549
Uh, my mother died when I was young.

1460
01:11:38.632 --> 01:11:39.748
Oh.

1461
01:11:39.831 --> 01:11:41.288
And your father?

1462
01:11:41.371 --> 01:11:42.751
(chuckles)

1463
01:11:42.834 --> 01:11:44.984
Let's just say I left home when I was 15.

1464
01:11:45.067 --> 01:11:46.623
-You ran away?
-Worse.

1465
01:11:46.706 --> 01:11:49.120
-I got a scholarship to Barton.
-Oh.

1466
01:11:49.203 --> 01:11:52.959
And from there, I went to
college and never looked back.

1467
01:11:53.042 --> 01:11:55.434
-Oh, but you did a little.
-Hmm?

1468
01:11:55.517 --> 01:11:57.469
I mean, you came back here.

1469
01:11:57.552 --> 01:11:59.570
Ah.

1470
01:11:59.653 --> 01:12:02.342
Feels kind of like home. Yes.

1471
01:12:02.425 --> 01:12:05.136
And I guess I thought
I could make a difference.

1472
01:12:05.219 --> 01:12:08.073
I mean, I used to think I could
prepare them for the world

1473
01:12:08.156 --> 01:12:09.613
-even a little.
-Mm-hmm.

1474
01:12:09.696 --> 01:12:11.142
Provide standards and grounding

1475
01:12:11.225 --> 01:12:13.078
like Dr. Greene always drilled into us.

1476
01:12:13.161 --> 01:12:15.421
But, uh, the world doesn't
make sense anymore.

1477
01:12:15.504 --> 01:12:18.523
(chuckles): I mean, it's on fire.

1478
01:12:18.606 --> 01:12:20.690
The rich don't give a shit.

1479
01:12:20.773 --> 01:12:22.692
Poor kids are cannon fodder.

1480
01:12:22.775 --> 01:12:24.859
Integrity is a punch line.

1481
01:12:24.942 --> 01:12:27.367
Trust is just a name on a bank.

1482
01:12:27.450 --> 01:12:28.665
(Miss Crane chuckles softly)

1483
01:12:28.748 --> 01:12:30.799
Well...

1484
01:12:30.882 --> 01:12:33.505
look, if that's all true,

1485
01:12:33.588 --> 01:12:37.394
then now is when they most need
someone like you.

1486
01:12:40.795 --> 01:12:43.273
(record scratching, skipping)

1487
01:12:43.356 --> 01:12:45.616
("When Winter Comes" by Artie
Shaw & His Orchestra playing)

1488
01:12:45.699 --> 01:12:51.017
Danny, did you know that
Curtis used to love Artie Shaw?

1489
01:12:51.100 --> 01:12:53.118
You know, we used to dance to this.

1490
01:12:53.201 --> 01:12:54.658
(chuckles)

1491
01:12:54.741 --> 01:12:57.645
What teenage kid you know
listens to Artie Shaw?

1492
01:13:00.078 --> 01:13:01.368
You're killing me.

1493
01:13:01.451 --> 01:13:02.534
Can't you play something a little hipper?

1494
01:13:02.617 --> 01:13:04.635
Don't touch that goddamn record.

1495
01:13:04.718 --> 01:13:06.637
DANNY: Hey, wait. Hey, M-Mary,
come on, just sit down.

1496
01:13:06.720 --> 01:13:08.199
-MARY: Oh, I'm okay.
-DANNY: All right.

1497
01:13:08.282 --> 01:13:10.476
-No, Danny, I'm okay.
-I-I know. Please.

1498
01:13:10.559 --> 01:13:13.479
-Okay, but I said I'm okay.
-Okay.

1499
01:13:13.562 --> 01:13:16.416
♪ And I'll be fine in the summer ♪

1500
01:13:16.499 --> 01:13:19.419
♪ But then I gotta have you
to cuddle up to ♪

1501
01:13:19.502 --> 01:13:21.867
♪ When winter comes. ♪

1502
01:13:25.367 --> 01:13:27.444
♪ ♪

1503
01:13:38.853 --> 01:13:40.952
Go get me another drink.

1504
01:13:42.527 --> 01:13:44.334
So, are you planning
anything special for tomorrow?

1505
01:13:44.417 --> 01:13:46.776
No. Why? Are you having, um...

1506
01:13:46.859 --> 01:13:48.877
Oh, no, no. I just...

1507
01:13:48.960 --> 01:13:51.583
I thought maybe you were doing
something special for Angus.

1508
01:13:51.666 --> 01:13:53.277
Oh.

1509
01:13:53.360 --> 01:13:54.619
("It's the Most Wonderful Time
of the Year" playing)

1510
01:13:54.702 --> 01:13:56.885
-You should.
-Oh.

1511
01:13:56.968 --> 01:13:59.217
Help preserve some of the magic.

1512
01:13:59.300 --> 01:14:02.429
I mean, he may be a little
difficult, but he's still...

1513
01:14:02.512 --> 01:14:04.431
-he's just a kid.
-Yeah.

1514
01:14:04.514 --> 01:14:08.567
Life catches up to them so fast.

1515
01:14:08.650 --> 01:14:10.817
Them. Ha.

1516
01:14:12.150 --> 01:14:14.315
-Us.
-Mm-hmm.

1517
01:14:17.188 --> 01:14:19.908
You're a very sweet person, Miss Crane.

1518
01:14:19.991 --> 01:14:22.581
Aw.

1519
01:14:22.664 --> 01:14:24.781
-So are you.
-(chuckles)

1520
01:14:24.864 --> 01:14:26.453
-When you want to be.
-Mm.

1521
01:14:26.536 --> 01:14:27.916
And it's Lydia.

1522
01:14:27.999 --> 01:14:30.067
Lydia. (chuckles)

1523
01:14:31.070 --> 01:14:33.037
(door opens)

1524
01:14:34.612 --> 01:14:36.496
-Excuse me for a minute.
-Mm.

1525
01:14:36.579 --> 01:14:38.680
Hi.

1526
01:14:41.850 --> 01:14:43.965
♪ There'll be much mistletoeing ♪

1527
01:14:44.048 --> 01:14:45.901
♪ And hearts will be glowing ♪

1528
01:14:45.984 --> 01:14:49.069
♪ When loved ones are near ♪

1529
01:14:49.152 --> 01:14:52.479
♪ It's the most wonderful time ♪

1530
01:14:52.562 --> 01:14:55.746
♪ Of the year... ♪

1531
01:14:55.829 --> 01:14:57.534
(sighs)

1532
01:14:58.768 --> 01:15:00.949
Mr. Hunham? Mr. Hunham,
could you come with me, please?

1533
01:15:01.032 --> 01:15:02.951
Yeah. What is it?

1534
01:15:03.034 --> 01:15:04.986
Come on. I'm serious.

1535
01:15:05.069 --> 01:15:06.906
(grunts)

1536
01:15:08.239 --> 01:15:10.288
-Come on.
-Yes.

1537
01:15:10.371 --> 01:15:12.455
♪ There'll be scary ghost stories ♪

1538
01:15:12.538 --> 01:15:14.798
-(Mary sobbing)
-♪ And tales of the glories ♪

1539
01:15:14.881 --> 01:15:17.867
♪ Of Christmases long, long ago... ♪

1540
01:15:17.950 --> 01:15:20.331
Mary?

1541
01:15:20.414 --> 01:15:22.333
You all right?

1542
01:15:22.416 --> 01:15:24.660
MARY: Just leave me alone.

1543
01:15:25.960 --> 01:15:27.547
You want me to take you home?

1544
01:15:27.630 --> 01:15:30.616
Back off! Back off.

1545
01:15:30.699 --> 01:15:32.618
♪ There'll be much mistletoeing ♪

1546
01:15:32.701 --> 01:15:34.818
♪ And hearts will be glowing... ♪

1547
01:15:34.901 --> 01:15:37.398
(song continues muffled in distance)

1548
01:15:40.106 --> 01:15:42.139
(Mary sniffling, crying)

1549
01:15:45.144 --> 01:15:47.408
He's gone.

1550
01:15:54.923 --> 01:15:57.022
(sighs)

1551
01:15:58.025 --> 01:15:59.139
PAUL: I was right.

1552
01:15:59.222 --> 01:16:00.745
This is why I hate parties.

1553
01:16:00.828 --> 01:16:02.714
That was a disaster. Total disaster.

1554
01:16:02.797 --> 01:16:04.881
Speak for yourself. I was having fun.

1555
01:16:04.964 --> 01:16:06.476
Let's take Mary home,

1556
01:16:06.559 --> 01:16:07.653
make sure she's okay, and we'll come back.

1557
01:16:07.736 --> 01:16:09.215
-Out of the question.
-Come on.

1558
01:16:09.298 --> 01:16:10.887
Would you give me a break?

1559
01:16:10.970 --> 01:16:12.559
I was hitting it off with Elise.

1560
01:16:12.642 --> 01:16:13.857
Oh. (chuckles) The niece?

1561
01:16:13.940 --> 01:16:15.056
Are you kidding me?

1562
01:16:15.139 --> 01:16:16.695
This poor woman is bereft,

1563
01:16:16.778 --> 01:16:18.598
and all you can think about
is some silly girl.

1564
01:16:18.681 --> 01:16:20.600
-Unbelievable.
-I don't need you feeling sorry for me.

1565
01:16:20.683 --> 01:16:23.834
See? I'm just saying,
this was the first good thing

1566
01:16:23.917 --> 01:16:26.265
that came with being
in this prison with you.

1567
01:16:26.348 --> 01:16:28.168
Need I remind you

1568
01:16:28.251 --> 01:16:30.500
that it is not my fault
that you are stuck here?

1569
01:16:30.583 --> 01:16:32.678
Do you think I want to be babysitting you?

1570
01:16:32.761 --> 01:16:36.110
Oh, no, no, I was praying to
the god I don't even believe in

1571
01:16:36.193 --> 01:16:37.947
that your mother would pick up the phone

1572
01:16:38.030 --> 01:16:41.588
or your father would arrive
in a helicopter or a submarine

1573
01:16:41.671 --> 01:16:43.722
or a flying fucking saucer to take you...

1574
01:16:43.805 --> 01:16:46.120
My father's dead.

1575
01:16:46.203 --> 01:16:47.726
(stammering): I thought your father...

1576
01:16:47.809 --> 01:16:51.026
That's just some rich guy my mom married.

1577
01:16:51.109 --> 01:16:53.193
Give me your keys.

1578
01:16:53.276 --> 01:16:55.179
It's unlocked.

1579
01:17:00.758 --> 01:17:04.567
You don't tell a boy that's
been left behind at Christmas

1580
01:17:04.650 --> 01:17:06.778
that you're aching to cut him loose.

1581
01:17:06.861 --> 01:17:08.813
That nobody wants him.

1582
01:17:08.896 --> 01:17:11.541
What the fuck is wrong with you?

1583
01:17:11.624 --> 01:17:14.165
Let's go. I'm cold.

1584
01:17:17.665 --> 01:17:19.401
(grunts softly)

1585
01:17:25.541 --> 01:17:30.934
♪ O little town of Bethlehem ♪

1586
01:17:31.017 --> 01:17:35.615
♪ How still we see thee lie ♪

1587
01:17:36.959 --> 01:17:42.308
♪ Above thy deep and dreamless sleep ♪

1588
01:17:42.391 --> 01:17:47.984
♪ The silent stars go by ♪

1589
01:17:48.067 --> 01:17:53.451
♪ Yet in thy dark streets shineth ♪

1590
01:17:53.534 --> 01:17:56.960
♪ The everlasting light... ♪

1591
01:17:57.043 --> 01:17:58.929
(car door closes)

1592
01:17:59.012 --> 01:18:00.799
-Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas.

1593
01:18:00.882 --> 01:18:02.295
What can I do for you, chief?

1594
01:18:02.378 --> 01:18:03.769
I'm looking for a tree.

1595
01:18:03.852 --> 01:18:05.298
Well, you came to the right place.

1596
01:18:05.381 --> 01:18:08.318
Big fire sale on all remaining inventory.

1597
01:18:10.960 --> 01:18:12.729
Mr. Tully.

1598
01:18:13.996 --> 01:18:15.798
Mr. Tully?

1599
01:18:17.725 --> 01:18:19.560
Mr. Tully.

1600
01:18:21.465 --> 01:18:23.789
Uh, Angus Tully!

1601
01:18:23.872 --> 01:18:25.940
(radio playing indistinctly)

1602
01:18:28.912 --> 01:18:30.125
(Paul sighs)

1603
01:18:30.208 --> 01:18:32.127
-Good morning.
-Merry Christmas.

1604
01:18:32.210 --> 01:18:33.964
Yeah. Merry Christmas, of course.

1605
01:18:34.047 --> 01:18:35.801
How are you?

1606
01:18:35.884 --> 01:18:38.034
Well, I've got a case of the cocktail flu.

1607
01:18:38.117 --> 01:18:40.630
-Yeah. Have you seen the boy?
-Mm-mm.

1608
01:18:40.713 --> 01:18:43.188
Goddammit, where the hell can he be?

1609
01:18:44.752 --> 01:18:46.686
Angus!

1610
01:18:48.591 --> 01:18:50.541
Mr. Tully?

1611
01:18:50.624 --> 01:18:52.752
(piano playing)

1612
01:18:52.835 --> 01:18:55.134
(panting)

1613
01:19:05.542 --> 01:19:08.015
-(door bangs shut)
-(playing stops)

1614
01:19:09.887 --> 01:19:12.739
-Merry Christmas.
-Merry Christmas.

1615
01:19:12.822 --> 01:19:14.499
Where the hell have you been?

1616
01:19:14.582 --> 01:19:17.172
I don't know. Just here.

1617
01:19:17.255 --> 01:19:19.174
Come on. I have something to show you.

1618
01:19:19.257 --> 01:19:21.325
♪ ♪

1619
01:19:25.034 --> 01:19:27.001
No ornaments?

1620
01:19:29.874 --> 01:19:33.419
Oh, I'm sure we can round up
some ornaments somewhere.

1621
01:19:33.502 --> 01:19:36.224
Uh, now...

1622
01:19:36.307 --> 01:19:39.079
this is for you.

1623
01:19:50.488 --> 01:19:53.538
<i>Meditations</i> by Marcus Aurelius.

1624
01:19:53.621 --> 01:19:55.881
For my money, it's like
the Bible, the Koran

1625
01:19:55.964 --> 01:19:58.576
and the Bhagavad Gita
all rolled up into one.

1626
01:19:58.659 --> 01:20:01.315
And the best part is
not one mention of God.

1627
01:20:01.398 --> 01:20:03.548
-Hmm.
-ANGUS: Okay.

1628
01:20:03.631 --> 01:20:05.435
Thanks.

1629
01:20:06.603 --> 01:20:09.257
And Mary.

1630
01:20:09.340 --> 01:20:11.243
This is for you.

1631
01:20:12.576 --> 01:20:14.213
Hmm.

1632
01:20:21.783 --> 01:20:23.667
So you just get this for everybody?

1633
01:20:23.750 --> 01:20:25.768
And...

1634
01:20:25.851 --> 01:20:27.638
-Mm-hmm.
-(Paul chuckling)

1635
01:20:27.721 --> 01:20:29.640
-Now, how'd you guess?
-How indeed?

1636
01:20:29.723 --> 01:20:30.982
(chuckles)

1637
01:20:31.065 --> 01:20:33.017
Oh, and...

1638
01:20:33.100 --> 01:20:35.300
this came in the mail for you.

1639
01:20:55.619 --> 01:20:57.652
♪ ♪

1640
01:21:05.431 --> 01:21:06.886
(Paul sighs)

1641
01:21:06.969 --> 01:21:09.020
Thank you, Mary.

1642
01:21:09.103 --> 01:21:10.989
That was just lovely.

1643
01:21:11.072 --> 01:21:12.287
Oh.

1644
01:21:12.370 --> 01:21:14.355
Is that an actual compliment?

1645
01:21:14.438 --> 01:21:17.193
-Oh, come on.
-(Mary laughs)

1646
01:21:17.276 --> 01:21:19.459
You know, I don't think I've ever had

1647
01:21:19.542 --> 01:21:22.792
a real family Christmas like this before.

1648
01:21:22.875 --> 01:21:25.234
Christmas dinner, I mean family-style.

1649
01:21:25.317 --> 01:21:28.072
Out of the oven and all the trimmings.

1650
01:21:28.155 --> 01:21:30.701
My mom always just orders in
from Delmonico's.

1651
01:21:30.784 --> 01:21:32.208
(Angus and Paul chuckle)

1652
01:21:32.291 --> 01:21:34.375
MARY: Well, she's got the right idea.

1653
01:21:34.458 --> 01:21:37.296
Next year I'm ordering in
from Delmonico's.

1654
01:21:39.135 --> 01:21:42.548
Anyway, thank you, Mary.

1655
01:21:42.631 --> 01:21:44.517
You're welcome.

1656
01:21:44.600 --> 01:21:46.519
PAUL: I'd like to propose a toast.

1657
01:21:46.602 --> 01:21:51.227
To my two unlikely companions
on this snowy island

1658
01:21:51.310 --> 01:21:56.183
and to our absent friends and family.

1659
01:21:58.187 --> 01:22:02.106
And I realize that none of us
is here because he wants to be.

1660
01:22:02.189 --> 01:22:05.208
So if there's any way
that I could make the holidays

1661
01:22:05.291 --> 01:22:07.947
a little cheerier for either one of you,

1662
01:22:08.030 --> 01:22:10.791
just say the word.

1663
01:22:11.728 --> 01:22:14.184
Okay.

1664
01:22:14.267 --> 01:22:15.955
I want to go to Boston.

1665
01:22:16.038 --> 01:22:17.616
Boston? Why?

1666
01:22:17.699 --> 01:22:19.420
Why not?

1667
01:22:19.503 --> 01:22:22.093
I want a real Christmas.
I want to go ice-skating.

1668
01:22:22.176 --> 01:22:23.688
I want to see a real Christmas tree

1669
01:22:23.771 --> 01:22:25.195
with real ornaments,
not that stupid thing.

1670
01:22:25.278 --> 01:22:27.362
-You said it was nice.
-MARY: It is nice.

1671
01:22:27.445 --> 01:22:29.265
ANGUS: Come on, let's get out of here.

1672
01:22:29.348 --> 01:22:31.069
I want a real holiday.

1673
01:22:31.152 --> 01:22:33.269
We're not going to Boston.
It's out of the question.

1674
01:22:33.352 --> 01:22:34.765
MARY: You told the boy "anything,"

1675
01:22:34.848 --> 01:22:36.239
so take the kid to Boston.

1676
01:22:36.322 --> 01:22:38.307
Mary, we're not allowed to leave campus

1677
01:22:38.390 --> 01:22:40.821
or the immediate environs.

1678
01:22:45.025 --> 01:22:46.497
(sighs)

1679
01:22:51.438 --> 01:22:52.959
(sighs heavily)

1680
01:22:53.042 --> 01:22:55.770
I suppose we could call it a field trip.

1681
01:22:56.839 --> 01:22:58.624
Uh, field trips would fall under the ambit

1682
01:22:58.707 --> 01:23:01.132
of additional academic pursuits.

1683
01:23:01.215 --> 01:23:02.793
There's even a fund set aside

1684
01:23:02.876 --> 01:23:05.400
for additional academic pursuits.

1685
01:23:05.483 --> 01:23:07.518
Mm-hmm.

1686
01:23:09.126 --> 01:23:11.456
I'll go pack. (laughs)

1687
01:23:13.427 --> 01:23:15.245
I'm gonna need you to take me to Roxbury.

1688
01:23:15.328 --> 01:23:17.759
Mm-hmm. All right.

1689
01:23:19.235 --> 01:23:21.268
♪ ♪

1690
01:23:41.455 --> 01:23:44.291
-♪ ♪
-(no dialogue)

1691
01:23:59.176 --> 01:24:01.242
♪ ♪

1692
01:24:13.751 --> 01:24:16.669
-MARY (sighs): Here we are.
-PAUL: Hmm.

1693
01:24:16.752 --> 01:24:19.870
Boy, that's an awful lot of stairs.

1694
01:24:19.953 --> 01:24:23.132
-Probably icy too.
-Mm.

1695
01:24:24.762 --> 01:24:26.025
Mr. Tully.

1696
01:24:27.028 --> 01:24:28.549
Right. Um...

1697
01:24:28.632 --> 01:24:30.749
Mary, can I help you with your bags?

1698
01:24:30.832 --> 01:24:32.801
MARY: Yes, please.

1699
01:24:41.614 --> 01:24:42.728
-PAUL: Hmm.
-(trunk closes)

1700
01:24:42.811 --> 01:24:44.516
MARY: Mm.

1701
01:24:45.684 --> 01:24:47.403
Hey, be careful with the box.

1702
01:24:47.486 --> 01:24:49.603
Yeah.

1703
01:24:49.686 --> 01:24:52.342
You know, you're more than
welcome to a room at the hotel.

1704
01:24:52.425 --> 01:24:53.739
We've got the money.

1705
01:24:53.822 --> 01:24:55.543
Are you out of your mind?

1706
01:24:55.626 --> 01:24:58.117
I need a break from you two
and all your damn bickering.

1707
01:24:58.200 --> 01:25:00.779
Besides, I'm looking forward
to visiting my little sister.

1708
01:25:00.862 --> 01:25:02.220
She's pregnant.

1709
01:25:02.303 --> 01:25:03.617
Oh, that's wonderful.

1710
01:25:03.700 --> 01:25:04.998
-Yeah.
-Oh.

1711
01:25:06.969 --> 01:25:09.051
-Mr. Hunham. Mr. Hunham.
-Oh, I'm sorry.

1712
01:25:09.134 --> 01:25:10.459
My hands sweat.

1713
01:25:10.542 --> 01:25:12.296
It's hyperhidrosis. Sorry.

1714
01:25:12.379 --> 01:25:13.809
-Oh.
-ANGUS: Hey, Mary!

1715
01:25:15.714 --> 01:25:18.077
One more flight up.

1716
01:25:19.080 --> 01:25:20.601
One more flight up.

1717
01:25:20.684 --> 01:25:22.031
Yep.

1718
01:25:22.114 --> 01:25:23.736
So, you two are going to be all right?

1719
01:25:23.819 --> 01:25:25.375
Yes, the little monster
will be well under control.

1720
01:25:25.458 --> 01:25:27.559
-PEGGY: Mary!
-Oh.

1721
01:25:28.562 --> 01:25:30.364
Hi!

1722
01:25:33.193 --> 01:25:35.237
-Bye.
-Bye.

1723
01:25:39.705 --> 01:25:40.984
Bye, Mary.

1724
01:25:41.067 --> 01:25:42.458
Uh-uh. Where are you going?

1725
01:25:42.541 --> 01:25:43.888
-I was...
-You're not done yet.

1726
01:25:43.971 --> 01:25:45.923
You have to help me up there.

1727
01:25:46.006 --> 01:25:48.415
-Yeah, sure thing.
-Come on.

1728
01:26:02.926 --> 01:26:05.696
(kids chattering playfully outside)

1729
01:26:16.280 --> 01:26:18.742
(opens drawer)

1730
01:26:24.046 --> 01:26:26.079
♪ ♪

1731
01:26:27.555 --> 01:26:30.050
(chuckles softly)

1732
01:26:50.105 --> 01:26:51.808
(Mary sighs softly)

1733
01:27:05.186 --> 01:27:07.263
(laughter, indistinct chatter)

1734
01:27:13.128 --> 01:27:15.012
(indistinct chatter continues)

1735
01:27:15.095 --> 01:27:17.163
♪ ♪

1736
01:27:29.782 --> 01:27:31.815
♪ ♪

1737
01:27:39.825 --> 01:27:41.858
(siren wailing in distance)

1738
01:27:48.471 --> 01:27:50.196
Hmm.

1739
01:27:54.334 --> 01:27:56.708
Hey there, handsome. You got a cigarette?

1740
01:27:57.744 --> 01:28:00.173
Nope. Sorry, I smoke a pipe.

1741
01:28:01.880 --> 01:28:04.144
How about a date, then? You want a date?

1742
01:28:05.147 --> 01:28:06.371
(chuckles)

1743
01:28:06.454 --> 01:28:07.603
No, thank you.

1744
01:28:07.686 --> 01:28:09.099
-Oh, come on.
-Mm-mm-mm.

1745
01:28:09.182 --> 01:28:10.936
Let's go somewhere warm.

1746
01:28:11.019 --> 01:28:12.773
Go ahead.

1747
01:28:12.856 --> 01:28:15.039
-I can wait here.
-WOMAN: See?

1748
01:28:15.122 --> 01:28:17.943
He can wait here, read some books.

1749
01:28:18.026 --> 01:28:20.979
He doesn't mind if daddy gets
a little candy cane.

1750
01:28:21.062 --> 01:28:24.488
Thank you, but I never really
liked candy canes.

1751
01:28:24.571 --> 01:28:26.672
Plus, I'm prediabetic.

1752
01:28:34.374 --> 01:28:36.731
You know, if you do want
a little candy cane,

1753
01:28:36.814 --> 01:28:38.898
I won't tell anyone.

1754
01:28:38.981 --> 01:28:42.638
Mr. Tully, for most people,
sex is 99% friction

1755
01:28:42.721 --> 01:28:44.409
and one percent goodwill.

1756
01:28:44.492 --> 01:28:46.004
Call me old-fashioned,

1757
01:28:46.087 --> 01:28:48.105
but I place value on physical intimacy.

1758
01:28:48.188 --> 01:28:50.272
So should you.

1759
01:28:50.355 --> 01:28:52.109
You've never had sex, have you?

1760
01:28:52.192 --> 01:28:53.946
(laughs)

1761
01:28:54.029 --> 01:28:56.080
Believe it or not, Mr. Tully,
there was a time

1762
01:28:56.163 --> 01:28:58.181
when the fire in my loins
burned white hot.

1763
01:28:58.264 --> 01:28:59.688
You're full of shit.

1764
01:28:59.771 --> 01:29:02.592
No, the details would curl your toes.

1765
01:29:02.675 --> 01:29:04.429
Okay, we're finally getting
to the good stuff.

1766
01:29:04.512 --> 01:29:05.958
Let's hear.

1767
01:29:06.041 --> 01:29:08.125
Maybe when you're eighteen.

1768
01:29:08.208 --> 01:29:10.633
Curl your toes!

1769
01:29:10.716 --> 01:29:12.784
♪ ♪

1770
01:29:21.795 --> 01:29:23.448
ANGUS: Are we almost done?

1771
01:29:23.531 --> 01:29:25.615
PAUL: What's your hurry?
I thought you liked antiquity.

1772
01:29:25.698 --> 01:29:27.210
(chuckles) In class, maybe,

1773
01:29:27.293 --> 01:29:29.311
but I never think about it
unless I need to.

1774
01:29:29.394 --> 01:29:32.523
Ah. Ah, well, here.

1775
01:29:32.606 --> 01:29:35.185
What do you see?

1776
01:29:35.268 --> 01:29:37.462
I don't know. A bunch of pottery.

1777
01:29:37.545 --> 01:29:40.581
Mm. Look at that one.

1778
01:29:48.525 --> 01:29:50.134
-Candy cane.
-(laughs): Yes.

1779
01:29:50.217 --> 01:29:54.039
There's nothing new
in human experience, Mr. Tully.

1780
01:29:54.122 --> 01:29:56.679
Each generation thinks
it invented debauchery

1781
01:29:56.762 --> 01:29:58.681
or suffering or rebellion,

1782
01:29:58.764 --> 01:30:01.684
but man's every impulse and appetite

1783
01:30:01.767 --> 01:30:03.983
from the disgusting to the sublime

1784
01:30:04.066 --> 01:30:08.053
is on display right here all around you.

1785
01:30:08.136 --> 01:30:09.890
So, before you dismiss something

1786
01:30:09.973 --> 01:30:11.826
as boring or irrelevant, remember,

1787
01:30:11.909 --> 01:30:15.324
if you truly want to understand
the present or yourself,

1788
01:30:15.407 --> 01:30:18.327
you must begin in the past.

1789
01:30:18.410 --> 01:30:21.099
You see, history is not simply
the study of the past.

1790
01:30:21.182 --> 01:30:24.185
It is an explanation of the present.

1791
01:30:26.629 --> 01:30:29.877
See, when you say it that way
and throw in some pornography,

1792
01:30:29.960 --> 01:30:31.879
it's a lot easier to understand.

1793
01:30:31.962 --> 01:30:33.848
(chuckles): Okay.

1794
01:30:33.931 --> 01:30:37.280
You should try doing more of
that in class and less yelling.

1795
01:30:37.363 --> 01:30:39.183
You know, most of the kids dislike you.

1796
01:30:39.266 --> 01:30:41.020
Pretty much hate you.

1797
01:30:41.103 --> 01:30:43.220
Teachers too.

1798
01:30:43.303 --> 01:30:45.024
You know that, right?

1799
01:30:45.107 --> 01:30:47.763
("The Wind" by Cat Stevens playing)

1800
01:30:47.846 --> 01:30:49.485
(chuckles softly)

1801
01:30:55.691 --> 01:31:00.353
♪ I listen to the wind,
to the wind of my soul ♪

1802
01:31:03.930 --> 01:31:08.867
♪ Where I'll end up, well,
I think only God really knows ♪

1803
01:31:12.840 --> 01:31:16.726
♪ I've sat upon the setting sun ♪

1804
01:31:16.809 --> 01:31:21.467
♪ But never, never, never, never ♪

1805
01:31:21.550 --> 01:31:25.471
♪ I never wanted water once ♪

1806
01:31:25.554 --> 01:31:28.953
♪ No, never, never, never ♪

1807
01:31:32.893 --> 01:31:36.746
♪ I never wanted water once ♪

1808
01:31:36.829 --> 01:31:40.030
♪ No, never, never, never. ♪

1809
01:31:43.068 --> 01:31:45.101
(quiet, indistinct chatter)

1810
01:31:46.643 --> 01:31:49.039
MAN: Paul Hunham! Is that you?

1811
01:31:51.274 --> 01:31:52.861
It's Hugh.

1812
01:31:52.944 --> 01:31:55.457
Hugh Cavanaugh.

1813
01:31:55.540 --> 01:31:58.130
Ah, yes. Of course.

1814
01:31:58.213 --> 01:31:59.934
Wow. Hugh Cavanaugh.

1815
01:32:00.017 --> 01:32:01.507
Wow.

1816
01:32:01.590 --> 01:32:03.608
Oh, how are you, Hugh?

1817
01:32:03.691 --> 01:32:06.776
Oh, God, what's it been, 30 years? Um...

1818
01:32:06.859 --> 01:32:09.174
Um, this-this is, uh...
this is my wife Karen.

1819
01:32:09.257 --> 01:32:12.045
Honey, this is Paul Hunham.

1820
01:32:12.128 --> 01:32:13.948
-We went to Harvard together.
-Hi, Paul.

1821
01:32:14.031 --> 01:32:16.621
Yes, we did. Yes, we did.

1822
01:32:16.704 --> 01:32:18.183
Uh, wow.

1823
01:32:18.266 --> 01:32:19.855
Uh, what have you been up to, Hugh?

1824
01:32:19.938 --> 01:32:21.956
-Uh, still in the area?
-HUGH: Oh, yes. Yes.

1825
01:32:22.039 --> 01:32:23.826
I-I'm still in Boston. Cambridge.

1826
01:32:23.909 --> 01:32:25.322
-Harvard.
-Well...

1827
01:32:25.405 --> 01:32:26.862
He just got tenure. Statistics.

1828
01:32:26.945 --> 01:32:28.996
-Oh, Karen.
-He won't blow his own horn.

1829
01:32:29.079 --> 01:32:31.064
-I have to blow it for him.
-Okay. Well, uh,

1830
01:32:31.147 --> 01:32:32.637
what about you, Paul?

1831
01:32:32.720 --> 01:32:34.298
Oh, still teaching.
We have that in common.

1832
01:32:34.381 --> 01:32:36.036
Uh, history, ancient history.

1833
01:32:36.119 --> 01:32:37.202
-That's great.
-PAUL: Yes.

1834
01:32:37.285 --> 01:32:38.467
That's great. Where?

1835
01:32:38.550 --> 01:32:41.173
Oh, um, abroad, mostly.

1836
01:32:41.256 --> 01:32:43.813
On fellowships,
privately funded fellowships.

1837
01:32:43.896 --> 01:32:45.650
Universities and private academies.

1838
01:32:45.733 --> 01:32:47.509
Mostly fellowships, you know.

1839
01:32:47.592 --> 01:32:50.182
I'm currently posted in, um, Antwerp.

1840
01:32:50.265 --> 01:32:52.723
Uh, just back here for the holidays.

1841
01:32:52.806 --> 01:32:54.758
Ah. So, uh, is this your son?

1842
01:32:54.841 --> 01:32:57.893
-Well, um...
-I'm his nephew, Leonard.

1843
01:32:57.976 --> 01:32:59.697
KAREN: Nice to meet you, Leonard.

1844
01:32:59.780 --> 01:33:01.424
And he's writing a book right now.

1845
01:33:01.507 --> 01:33:03.063
Um, tell him about your book, Uncle Paul.

1846
01:33:03.146 --> 01:33:04.735
(chuckles): My book.

1847
01:33:04.818 --> 01:33:06.396
It's not a book, really.

1848
01:33:06.479 --> 01:33:08.002
Uh, more of a monograph.

1849
01:33:08.085 --> 01:33:10.103
-It's nothing special.
-Don't be so modest.

1850
01:33:10.186 --> 01:33:12.677
It's about, uh, cameras, right?
Ancient cameras?

1851
01:33:12.760 --> 01:33:14.371
-Oh.
-PAUL: Yes.

1852
01:33:14.454 --> 01:33:17.077
No, what he means, of course,
is the camera obscura.

1853
01:33:17.160 --> 01:33:19.618
You know, the optical
and astronomical tool

1854
01:33:19.701 --> 01:33:22.445
that dates back to the time
of, um, Anaxagoras.

1855
01:33:22.528 --> 01:33:24.117
Tell him the title, Uncle Paul.

1856
01:33:24.200 --> 01:33:25.723
He's not interested, Leonard.

1857
01:33:25.806 --> 01:33:27.890
Sure, I am.

1858
01:33:27.973 --> 01:33:29.760
(sighs)

1859
01:33:29.843 --> 01:33:34.540
<i>Light and Magic in the Ancient World.</i>

1860
01:33:36.720 --> 01:33:39.198
Okay, well, um...

1861
01:33:39.281 --> 01:33:41.987
Paul, I'm just so glad
you landed on your feet.

1862
01:33:42.990 --> 01:33:44.269
You look swell.

1863
01:33:44.352 --> 01:33:46.255
You too. So swell.

1864
01:33:47.863 --> 01:33:50.077
And, uh, we'll keep an eye out
for your book.

1865
01:33:50.160 --> 01:33:51.474
-Won't we, honey?
-Yeah.

1866
01:33:51.557 --> 01:33:52.948
-Merry Christmas, Paul.
-Merry Christmas.

1867
01:33:53.031 --> 01:33:55.099
-Bye, Leonard.
-Merry Christmas.

1868
01:33:57.499 --> 01:33:59.383
What the fuck just happened?

1869
01:33:59.466 --> 01:34:02.485
I thought Barton men don't lie.

1870
01:34:02.568 --> 01:34:04.223
Don't get me wrong, that was fun,

1871
01:34:04.306 --> 01:34:05.763
but you just lied through your teeth.

1872
01:34:05.846 --> 01:34:07.589
What I say during a private conversation

1873
01:34:07.672 --> 01:34:09.393
is none of your goddamn business.

1874
01:34:09.476 --> 01:34:11.065
You are not to judge me.

1875
01:34:11.148 --> 01:34:12.803
It wasn't a private conversation.

1876
01:34:12.886 --> 01:34:14.332
-The wife and I were there.
-(groans)

1877
01:34:14.415 --> 01:34:15.938
-And I helped you.
-(Paul laughs)

1878
01:34:16.021 --> 01:34:17.775
Why did he ask if you landed on your feet?

1879
01:34:17.858 --> 01:34:19.436
What is this, Nuremberg?

1880
01:34:19.519 --> 01:34:21.075
-Jesus.
-You're the hard-ass

1881
01:34:21.158 --> 01:34:22.681
constantly telling everybody not to lie

1882
01:34:22.764 --> 01:34:25.063
and going on and on about the honor code.

1883
01:34:26.803 --> 01:34:28.753
There was an incident
when I was at Harvard

1884
01:34:28.836 --> 01:34:31.085
with my roommate.

1885
01:34:31.168 --> 01:34:32.988
And?

1886
01:34:33.071 --> 01:34:35.518
He accused me of copying
from his senior thesis.

1887
01:34:35.601 --> 01:34:36.794
Plagiarizing.

1888
01:34:36.877 --> 01:34:38.191
Ah.

1889
01:34:38.274 --> 01:34:41.865
-Well, did you?
-No, he stole from me.

1890
01:34:41.948 --> 01:34:43.493
But that blue-blooded prick's family

1891
01:34:43.576 --> 01:34:45.363
had allies on the faculty.

1892
01:34:45.446 --> 01:34:47.497
I mean, their last name is on
a library, for Christ's sake.

1893
01:34:47.580 --> 01:34:50.808
So he accused me in order
to sanitize his treachery

1894
01:34:50.891 --> 01:34:54.009
and, uh, they threw me out.

1895
01:34:54.092 --> 01:34:56.374
Wait, so you got kicked out
of Harvard for cheating?

1896
01:34:56.457 --> 01:34:58.508
No, I got kicked out of Harvard
for hitting him.

1897
01:34:58.591 --> 01:34:59.982
-(Paul chuckles)
-You hit him?

1898
01:35:00.065 --> 01:35:01.214
What, like punched him out?

1899
01:35:01.297 --> 01:35:03.546
No, I hit him with a car. Ah.

1900
01:35:03.629 --> 01:35:06.285
You got kicked out of Harvard
for hitting a guy with a car?

1901
01:35:06.368 --> 01:35:07.792
By accident.

1902
01:35:07.875 --> 01:35:10.058
Pint of Jim Beam, please.

1903
01:35:10.141 --> 01:35:13.160
But he broke three ribs,
which was technically his fault

1904
01:35:13.243 --> 01:35:14.799
because he shouldn't have been
in the road.

1905
01:35:14.882 --> 01:35:16.493
CASHIER: Two dollars, please.

1906
01:35:16.576 --> 01:35:18.528
-Also, he shat himself.
-(cash register bell dings)

1907
01:35:18.611 --> 01:35:20.332
Which was the greater indignity.

1908
01:35:20.415 --> 01:35:22.153
(laughs)

1909
01:35:23.156 --> 01:35:24.584
Here you go, killer.

1910
01:35:25.620 --> 01:35:27.471
(cash register drawer closes)

1911
01:35:27.554 --> 01:35:29.847
ANGUS: So Mr. Hunham
never even graduated college?

1912
01:35:29.930 --> 01:35:31.541
-PAUL: Mm.
-Holy shit.

1913
01:35:31.624 --> 01:35:33.345
You didn't finish up
somewhere else? Who else knows?

1914
01:35:33.428 --> 01:35:35.248
Well, Dr. Greene knew.

1915
01:35:35.331 --> 01:35:37.756
Only Dr. Greene.

1916
01:35:37.839 --> 01:35:40.682
He always believed in me,
so he gave me a job.

1917
01:35:40.765 --> 01:35:44.323
Adjunct faculty,
zero respect and even less pay.

1918
01:35:44.406 --> 01:35:46.160
So nobody batted an eye,

1919
01:35:46.243 --> 01:35:48.360
and I've been at the school ever since.

1920
01:35:48.443 --> 01:35:50.197
Are you ashamed at how things turned out?

1921
01:35:50.280 --> 01:35:53.167
Not at all. I'm proud of my work.

1922
01:35:53.250 --> 01:35:55.367
I love history. I love Barton.

1923
01:35:55.450 --> 01:35:57.006
Barton is my life.

1924
01:35:57.089 --> 01:35:59.008
I don't know what I would do
without Barton.

1925
01:35:59.091 --> 01:36:00.779
Why'd you lie to that guy?

1926
01:36:00.862 --> 01:36:03.111
Because I knew he'd relish
the fact that I'm a washout

1927
01:36:03.194 --> 01:36:04.948
and never left my own high school,

1928
01:36:05.031 --> 01:36:06.675
and he'd probably repeat that story

1929
01:36:06.758 --> 01:36:08.446
to everybody we used to know,

1930
01:36:08.529 --> 01:36:11.614
so I figured he's not
entitled to my story.

1931
01:36:11.697 --> 01:36:13.055
I am.

1932
01:36:13.138 --> 01:36:14.958
Yeah. Yeah, fuck that guy.

1933
01:36:15.041 --> 01:36:18.060
Yeah, exactly. Fuck that guy.

1934
01:36:18.143 --> 01:36:20.590
"Statistics." (scoffs)

1935
01:36:20.673 --> 01:36:23.560
But, now, you'll keep this quiet, right?

1936
01:36:23.643 --> 01:36:25.397
No one is to know.

1937
01:36:25.480 --> 01:36:28.136
I mean no one, Angus.

1938
01:36:28.219 --> 01:36:30.369
Entre nous, sir.

1939
01:36:30.452 --> 01:36:32.569
Entre nous.

1940
01:36:32.652 --> 01:36:34.109
"Ancient cameras."

1941
01:36:34.192 --> 01:36:35.946
Where the hell did you come up with that?

1942
01:36:36.029 --> 01:36:38.129
Just trying to keep you on your toes, sir.

1943
01:36:47.207 --> 01:36:48.877
Get up, kid.

1944
01:36:49.946 --> 01:36:51.946
It's daylight in the swamp.

1945
01:36:53.917 --> 01:36:55.851
I ordered breakfast.

1946
01:36:57.085 --> 01:36:59.415
Great. (sighs)

1947
01:37:10.626 --> 01:37:12.917
Oh, you dropped something.

1948
01:37:13.000 --> 01:37:14.952
(Paul grunts)

1949
01:37:15.035 --> 01:37:17.152
Uh, those are my vitamins.

1950
01:37:17.235 --> 01:37:18.956
Librium.

1951
01:37:19.039 --> 01:37:20.826
Yeah, it's just, uh,

1952
01:37:20.909 --> 01:37:23.092
something I'm supposed to take
for low energy.

1953
01:37:23.175 --> 01:37:25.210
You mean depression?

1954
01:37:26.444 --> 01:37:27.789
Is that rye toast?

1955
01:37:27.872 --> 01:37:30.314
How'd you know I like rye toast?

1956
01:37:39.963 --> 01:37:42.821
(sighs)

1957
01:37:51.238 --> 01:37:53.271
♪ ♪

1958
01:37:57.112 --> 01:37:59.145
(busy chatter)

1959
01:38:04.317 --> 01:38:07.021
All right. This way.

1960
01:38:17.660 --> 01:38:19.693
♪ ♪

1961
01:38:38.219 --> 01:38:39.878
(pins clatter)

1962
01:38:46.788 --> 01:38:47.963
(chuckles)

1963
01:38:49.329 --> 01:38:50.542
Let go lightly.

1964
01:38:50.625 --> 01:38:52.033
-Ah.
-You're too rigid.

1965
01:38:58.569 --> 01:39:00.123
(pins clatter)

1966
01:39:00.206 --> 01:39:01.619
-See?
-(Paul laughs)

1967
01:39:01.702 --> 01:39:03.225
-You're welcome.
-Not bad.

1968
01:39:03.308 --> 01:39:05.590
You're a pretty good teacher, kid.

1969
01:39:05.673 --> 01:39:07.427
Too bad everybody dislikes you.

1970
01:39:07.510 --> 01:39:09.198
Pretty much hates you.

1971
01:39:09.281 --> 01:39:11.844
But you must know that, right?

1972
01:39:12.847 --> 01:39:15.254
Touché, sir. Touché.

1973
01:39:18.919 --> 01:39:20.638
-By the way...
-Yeah?

1974
01:39:20.721 --> 01:39:22.805
...what eye do you aim with, anyway?

1975
01:39:22.888 --> 01:39:24.213
Ah.

1976
01:39:24.296 --> 01:39:25.808
You know, I've been meaning to ask.

1977
01:39:25.891 --> 01:39:27.909
When we're talking,
which one should I look at?

1978
01:39:27.992 --> 01:39:29.812
Sometimes I look at one,

1979
01:39:29.895 --> 01:39:32.386
but then I think I'm wrong,
so I look at the other.

1980
01:39:32.469 --> 01:39:34.553
Yes, everybody does that.

1981
01:39:34.636 --> 01:39:36.324
So, which eye is it?

1982
01:39:36.407 --> 01:39:38.112
(chuckles)

1983
01:39:39.742 --> 01:39:41.775
(lively chatter)

1984
01:39:54.229 --> 01:39:57.246
(scoffs) People don't understand.

1985
01:39:57.329 --> 01:39:59.149
This isn't tenpin.

1986
01:39:59.232 --> 01:40:00.986
No, this is much harder.

1987
01:40:01.069 --> 01:40:02.482
All these tenpin assholes

1988
01:40:02.565 --> 01:40:04.121
coming in here like they're slumming it.

1989
01:40:04.204 --> 01:40:05.485
-The hell with them.
-(grunts)

1990
01:40:05.568 --> 01:40:07.207
Yeah. Fuck 'em.

1991
01:40:10.036 --> 01:40:11.953
Excuse me.

1992
01:40:12.036 --> 01:40:14.131
Here's something I bet you didn't know.

1993
01:40:14.214 --> 01:40:19.136
Your uniform, festive as it is,
is historically inaccurate.

1994
01:40:19.219 --> 01:40:22.337
Saint Nicholas of Myra was actually

1995
01:40:22.420 --> 01:40:25.373
a fourth-century Greek Bishop
from what is now Turkey.

1996
01:40:25.456 --> 01:40:28.871
So, uh, a robe and sandals
would be closer to the mark.

1997
01:40:28.954 --> 01:40:32.017
Yeah, but I guess that would be
impractical given the weather

1998
01:40:32.100 --> 01:40:34.547
and all the silly but lucrative
mythology about Santa

1999
01:40:34.630 --> 01:40:38.122
and elves and reindeer
and chimneys and whatnot.

2000
01:40:38.205 --> 01:40:39.882
(chuckles) What can you do?

2001
01:40:39.965 --> 01:40:41.488
As Democritus said,

2002
01:40:41.571 --> 01:40:46.856
<i>"O kósmos alloíosis, o víos ypólipsis."</i>

2003
01:40:46.939 --> 01:40:51.009
"World is decay. Life is perception."

2004
01:40:57.457 --> 01:40:59.968
My son.

2005
01:41:00.051 --> 01:41:03.576
To see you again causes
my heart to soar like a hawk.

2006
01:41:03.659 --> 01:41:08.218
Grandfather, I brought you this present.

2007
01:41:08.301 --> 01:41:10.649
Is this the hat I used to own?

2008
01:41:10.732 --> 01:41:13.190
-(Paul chuckles)
-Except grown softer...

2009
01:41:13.273 --> 01:41:15.192
You know, this is not only amusing,

2010
01:41:15.275 --> 01:41:17.359
uh, but for a movie,
it's a fairly accurate depiction

2011
01:41:17.442 --> 01:41:19.020
of life among the Cheyenne.

2012
01:41:19.103 --> 01:41:21.198
-Shh!
-Fuck off.

2013
01:41:21.281 --> 01:41:23.332
(in movie): I saw you in a dream.

2014
01:41:23.415 --> 01:41:24.927
-I'm gonna go use the bathroom.
-Mm-hmm.

2015
01:41:25.010 --> 01:41:26.566
(in movie):
You were drinking from a spring

2016
01:41:26.649 --> 01:41:29.272
that came from the long nose of an animal.

2017
01:41:29.355 --> 01:41:33.342
I did not recognize the animal.

2018
01:41:33.425 --> 01:41:37.379
Alongside his nose, he grew two horns.

2019
01:41:37.462 --> 01:41:39.530
(movie continues playing indistinctly)

2020
01:41:51.511 --> 01:41:53.758
(in movie): ...and smoked on this matter,

2021
01:41:53.841 --> 01:41:56.365
and my decision is...

2022
01:41:56.448 --> 01:41:58.565
Little Big Man has returned.

2023
01:41:58.648 --> 01:42:00.716
(cheering, whooping in movie)

2024
01:42:04.018 --> 01:42:06.051
(quiet chatter)

2025
01:42:11.531 --> 01:42:14.433
PAUL: Hey! Hey!

2026
01:42:15.568 --> 01:42:17.601
No. Out.

2027
01:42:19.165 --> 01:42:20.719
Get out.

2028
01:42:20.802 --> 01:42:22.622
I just need to do something.
I was going to come back.

2029
01:42:22.705 --> 01:42:24.085
Or meet you at the hotel.

2030
01:42:24.168 --> 01:42:25.757
It won't take long. It's nothing bad.

2031
01:42:25.840 --> 01:42:29.629
Just get out, you conniving little shit.

2032
01:42:29.712 --> 01:42:31.961
(sighs)

2033
01:42:32.044 --> 01:42:34.304
Were you planning this the whole time?

2034
01:42:34.387 --> 01:42:36.966
Just counting the minutes
until I turned my back?

2035
01:42:37.049 --> 01:42:38.506
I wasn't running away.

2036
01:42:38.589 --> 01:42:39.936
There's just something I need to do

2037
01:42:40.019 --> 01:42:41.146
before we go back to school.

2038
01:42:41.229 --> 01:42:42.345
Please.

2039
01:42:42.428 --> 01:42:43.643
You could come with me.

2040
01:42:43.726 --> 01:42:44.941
Just come with me, okay?

2041
01:42:45.024 --> 01:42:46.927
Come with you where?

2042
01:42:48.227 --> 01:42:50.205
To see my dad.

2043
01:42:51.637 --> 01:42:53.455
Your dad?

2044
01:42:53.538 --> 01:42:55.083
(sighs)

2045
01:42:55.166 --> 01:42:57.085
That's what this is about?

2046
01:42:57.168 --> 01:42:59.758
Why didn't you just ask me?

2047
01:42:59.841 --> 01:43:03.075
Because, of course,
we can visit a cemetery.

2048
01:43:07.653 --> 01:43:09.719
♪ ♪

2049
01:43:22.162 --> 01:43:24.239
♪ ♪

2050
01:43:28.476 --> 01:43:30.525
Excuse me. Hi.

2051
01:43:30.608 --> 01:43:32.692
I'm here to see Thomas Tully.

2052
01:43:32.775 --> 01:43:34.843
♪ ♪

2053
01:43:46.989 --> 01:43:48.857
Right in here.

2054
01:44:03.445 --> 01:44:05.104
ORDERLY: Over here.

2055
01:44:07.779 --> 01:44:09.812
Look who's here to see you.

2056
01:44:14.555 --> 01:44:16.324
Hi, Dad.

2057
01:44:17.360 --> 01:44:19.393
Hello, sweetheart.

2058
01:44:39.140 --> 01:44:41.679
You want to go sit down for a little?

2059
01:44:43.881 --> 01:44:46.601
Oh. Come on.

2060
01:44:46.684 --> 01:44:48.752
Be seated right here.

2061
01:44:53.220 --> 01:44:55.594
There you go. All right.

2062
01:45:06.772 --> 01:45:09.426
I missed you.

2063
01:45:09.509 --> 01:45:12.055
I've missed you a lot.

2064
01:45:12.138 --> 01:45:14.107
A whole lot.

2065
01:45:16.881 --> 01:45:19.211
You know, I'm still at school.

2066
01:45:20.214 --> 01:45:21.603
At Barton.

2067
01:45:21.686 --> 01:45:23.132
And it's, uh... it's Christmastime now,

2068
01:45:23.215 --> 01:45:25.624
so I thought you might like a visit.

2069
01:45:28.354 --> 01:45:29.941
Guess what. I'm...

2070
01:45:30.024 --> 01:45:32.515
I'm actually keeping my grades up.

2071
01:45:32.598 --> 01:45:34.242
I-I consistently get

2072
01:45:34.325 --> 01:45:36.112
the highest grades in the class
in ancient civ.

2073
01:45:36.195 --> 01:45:39.704
I'm... I'm pretty much
third or fourth in precalc.

2074
01:45:43.072 --> 01:45:45.446
And I'm in the chess club too.

2075
01:45:46.878 --> 01:45:48.531
But I don't really like the other kids.

2076
01:45:48.614 --> 01:45:50.110
(chuckles softly)

2077
01:45:51.377 --> 01:45:54.372
And in the spring,
I think I want to try tennis.

2078
01:45:54.455 --> 01:45:56.033
Just JV, and probably only doubles,

2079
01:45:56.116 --> 01:45:58.954
if the coach could just forget
about my, uh...

2080
01:46:00.254 --> 01:46:02.287
Anyway, it's not important.

2081
01:46:10.297 --> 01:46:11.637
Listen.

2082
01:46:18.745 --> 01:46:21.647
I, uh... I have to tell you something.

2083
01:46:26.082 --> 01:46:28.852
I think they're putting
something in my food.

2084
01:46:38.534 --> 01:46:40.600
♪ ♪

2085
01:47:03.317 --> 01:47:05.707
He used to be fine.

2086
01:47:05.790 --> 01:47:08.237
He was better than fine.

2087
01:47:08.320 --> 01:47:10.157
He was great.

2088
01:47:11.534 --> 01:47:13.699
He was my dad.

2089
01:47:16.000 --> 01:47:18.588
Then about four years ago, he...

2090
01:47:18.671 --> 01:47:20.706
started acting strange.

2091
01:47:22.138 --> 01:47:24.875
Erratic, forgetful,
saying all this weird shit.

2092
01:47:27.407 --> 01:47:30.435
My mom took him to a bunch of doctors,

2093
01:47:30.518 --> 01:47:32.063
and they put him on medication.

2094
01:47:32.146 --> 01:47:35.099
But that just made it worse.

2095
01:47:35.182 --> 01:47:37.217
He got more confused.

2096
01:47:39.320 --> 01:47:41.221
Then he got angry.

2097
01:47:43.698 --> 01:47:46.143
And then he got...

2098
01:47:46.226 --> 01:47:48.327
physical.

2099
01:47:50.364 --> 01:47:51.951
That was it. That was the last straw.

2100
01:47:52.034 --> 01:47:53.871
They put him away.

2101
01:47:55.402 --> 01:47:58.760
And she divorced him...

2102
01:47:58.843 --> 01:48:01.043
without him even realizing it.

2103
01:48:02.717 --> 01:48:05.047
That's why she wants a whole new life.

2104
01:48:06.622 --> 01:48:08.836
And it's easy to just stash me
away in boarding school.

2105
01:48:08.919 --> 01:48:11.592
Like half of us
are just stashed away there.

2106
01:48:14.190 --> 01:48:16.025
And I get it.

2107
01:48:17.897 --> 01:48:20.062
She never has to look at me.

2108
01:48:22.099 --> 01:48:25.149
Because maybe when she looks at me, she...

2109
01:48:25.232 --> 01:48:28.449
-she sees him.
-No, no, no, no, no.

2110
01:48:28.532 --> 01:48:32.189
That can't be true. She... You're her son.

2111
01:48:32.272 --> 01:48:34.631
Maybe she's right.

2112
01:48:34.714 --> 01:48:36.633
I can't keep it together.

2113
01:48:36.716 --> 01:48:38.949
I lie. I steal.

2114
01:48:40.282 --> 01:48:42.249
I piss people off.

2115
01:48:43.582 --> 01:48:45.103
I don't have any friends, real friends.

2116
01:48:45.186 --> 01:48:46.709
I'll probably get kicked
out of Barton too.

2117
01:48:46.792 --> 01:48:49.091
And when I do, it'll be my own fault.

2118
01:48:50.666 --> 01:48:54.965
Get sent to Fork Union
and maybe to you-know-where.

2119
01:48:56.837 --> 01:48:59.002
And nobody will care.

2120
01:49:02.469 --> 01:49:04.502
The funny thing is...

2121
01:49:06.748 --> 01:49:09.749
I wanted to see him so bad
this whole time.

2122
01:49:16.351 --> 01:49:18.450
But I also didn't, you know?

2123
01:49:21.488 --> 01:49:23.009
Because I'm afraid

2124
01:49:23.092 --> 01:49:24.307
that's what's going to happen
to me one day.

2125
01:49:24.390 --> 01:49:25.979
No, Angus, Angus.

2126
01:49:26.062 --> 01:49:27.750
Angus, listen.

2127
01:49:27.833 --> 01:49:30.099
You're not your father.

2128
01:49:31.267 --> 01:49:32.755
How do you know?

2129
01:49:32.838 --> 01:49:35.417
Because no one is his own father.

2130
01:49:35.500 --> 01:49:37.188
I'm not my dad.

2131
01:49:37.271 --> 01:49:40.274
No matter how hard he tried
to beat that idea into me.

2132
01:49:46.315 --> 01:49:50.036
I find the world a bitter
and complicated place,

2133
01:49:50.119 --> 01:49:53.105
and it seems to feel
the same way about me.

2134
01:49:53.188 --> 01:49:55.487
I think you and I have this in common.

2135
01:49:56.963 --> 01:49:59.782
But don't get me wrong,
you have your challenges.

2136
01:49:59.865 --> 01:50:01.509
You're erratic and belligerent

2137
01:50:01.592 --> 01:50:03.412
and a gigantic pain in the balls,

2138
01:50:03.495 --> 01:50:05.381
but you're not your father.

2139
01:50:05.464 --> 01:50:08.005
You're your own man.

2140
01:50:10.339 --> 01:50:12.388
Man, no. You're just a kid.

2141
01:50:12.471 --> 01:50:14.126
You're just beginning.

2142
01:50:14.209 --> 01:50:16.211
And you're smart.

2143
01:50:17.412 --> 01:50:20.347
You've got time to turn things around.

2144
01:50:22.219 --> 01:50:24.268
Yes, I know the Greeks had the idea

2145
01:50:24.351 --> 01:50:26.611
that, uh, the steps you take
to avoid your fate

2146
01:50:26.694 --> 01:50:28.613
are the very steps that lead you to it,

2147
01:50:28.696 --> 01:50:30.615
but that's just a literary conceit.

2148
01:50:30.698 --> 01:50:32.617
In real life, your history

2149
01:50:32.700 --> 01:50:34.883
does not have to dictate your destiny...

2150
01:50:34.966 --> 01:50:37.413
Oh. There's Mary.

2151
01:50:37.496 --> 01:50:39.657
Can you not tell Mary or anybody? Uh...

2152
01:50:39.740 --> 01:50:42.418
Entre nous. This whole
goddamned trip is entre nous.

2153
01:50:42.501 --> 01:50:44.778
-Stand up.
-What?

2154
01:50:45.880 --> 01:50:47.665
Stand up for the lady, you boor.

2155
01:50:47.748 --> 01:50:49.882
You cretin.

2156
01:50:53.283 --> 01:50:54.837
-ANGUS: Mary.
-PAUL: Well, hello.

2157
01:50:54.920 --> 01:50:56.905
Hi. Sorry I'm late.

2158
01:50:56.988 --> 01:50:58.599
PAUL: Oh, we're just happy to see you.

2159
01:50:58.682 --> 01:51:00.271
-(Mary chuckles)
-(Paul grunts)

2160
01:51:00.354 --> 01:51:01.679
Madame, the menu.

2161
01:51:01.762 --> 01:51:03.648
MARY: Oh. Thank you.

2162
01:51:03.731 --> 01:51:05.848
Hello, ma'am. Would you like
a cocktail to start?

2163
01:51:05.931 --> 01:51:07.850
Oh, no, I'll just take a cup of tea.

2164
01:51:07.933 --> 01:51:09.280
Oh, come on. Have a cocktail.

2165
01:51:09.363 --> 01:51:10.952
No, no, no. A cup of tea is fine.

2166
01:51:11.035 --> 01:51:12.954
I've eaten already.

2167
01:51:13.037 --> 01:51:15.759
And you gentlemen,
did you save room for dessert?

2168
01:51:15.842 --> 01:51:18.289
-PAUL: Hmm.
-Hey, what's that?

2169
01:51:18.372 --> 01:51:20.159
WAITRESS: That's our signature dessert.

2170
01:51:20.242 --> 01:51:21.699
-Cherries jubilee.
-PAUL: Mmm.

2171
01:51:21.782 --> 01:51:23.426
-That sounds great.
-(Paul chuckles)

2172
01:51:23.509 --> 01:51:25.934
Bring the young vandal here
cherries jubilee.

2173
01:51:26.017 --> 01:51:27.804
I'm afraid I can't.

2174
01:51:27.887 --> 01:51:29.773
The dish contains brandy.

2175
01:51:29.856 --> 01:51:32.138
Same deal with the bananas Foster.

2176
01:51:32.221 --> 01:51:34.173
-Yeah, but doesn't the alcohol just burn off?
-PAUL: Mm.

2177
01:51:34.256 --> 01:51:36.010
WAITRESS: It's still
against the rules, ma'am.

2178
01:51:36.093 --> 01:51:37.638
-Fine.
-Oh.

2179
01:51:37.721 --> 01:51:39.640
I'll order the cherries
jubilee. We can share it.

2180
01:51:39.723 --> 01:51:42.148
Mm. I can't allow that, either.

2181
01:51:42.231 --> 01:51:44.546
Can we say it's his birthday?

2182
01:51:44.629 --> 01:51:46.053
It's my birthday.

2183
01:51:46.136 --> 01:51:48.121
Well, happy birthday, young man.

2184
01:51:48.204 --> 01:51:49.892
Let's get you a slice of cake

2185
01:51:49.975 --> 01:51:51.696
or some other age-appropriate dessert.

2186
01:51:51.779 --> 01:51:53.621
Christ on a crutch.

2187
01:51:53.704 --> 01:51:56.982
What kind of a fascist hash
foundry are you running here?

2188
01:51:59.822 --> 01:52:02.522
Uh, excuse me, ma'am. Do you,
by chance, have cherries?

2189
01:52:03.518 --> 01:52:05.039
Yes.

2190
01:52:05.122 --> 01:52:07.470
Great. And do you have ice cream?

2191
01:52:07.553 --> 01:52:09.637
-Yes.
-MARY: Fantastic.

2192
01:52:09.720 --> 01:52:13.047
Can we please get cherries
and ice cream to go?

2193
01:52:13.130 --> 01:52:14.675
And the check.

2194
01:52:14.758 --> 01:52:16.837
Right away.

2195
01:52:17.840 --> 01:52:19.840
-Bitch.
-Mm.

2196
01:52:25.045 --> 01:52:27.424
PAUL: And a little James Beam.

2197
01:52:27.507 --> 01:52:29.707
All right. Go ahead.

2198
01:52:31.986 --> 01:52:34.365
Ooh. (laughs)

2199
01:52:34.448 --> 01:52:36.004
Presto. Cherries jubilee.

2200
01:52:36.087 --> 01:52:37.698
(laughter)

2201
01:52:37.781 --> 01:52:39.337
Ooh.

2202
01:52:39.420 --> 01:52:41.504
-Shouldn't it just go out?
-Okay.

2203
01:52:41.587 --> 01:52:43.913
-(laughs)
-Oh, shit. Shit.

2204
01:52:43.996 --> 01:52:46.179
-How much alcohol did you put on there?
-Oh!

2205
01:52:46.262 --> 01:52:47.851
It's hot. It's very hot.

2206
01:52:47.934 --> 01:52:49.380
-Oh!
-(Mary squeals)

2207
01:52:49.463 --> 01:52:51.415
(laughter)

2208
01:52:51.498 --> 01:52:53.566
♪ ♪

2209
01:53:13.555 --> 01:53:15.588
♪ ♪

2210
01:53:17.493 --> 01:53:19.212
HOST (on TV): But now just listen to them.

2211
01:53:19.295 --> 01:53:20.741
They see the ball and...

2212
01:53:20.824 --> 01:53:22.578
MARY: Man, I sure do wish
we had some noisemakers.

2213
01:53:22.661 --> 01:53:23.838
PAUL: Mm-hmm.

2214
01:53:25.072 --> 01:53:27.319
I've got a noisemaker.

2215
01:53:27.402 --> 01:53:29.123
Where the hell did you get that?

2216
01:53:29.206 --> 01:53:30.993
I don't know. Found it.

2217
01:53:31.076 --> 01:53:33.424
Well, you're not deploying that in here.

2218
01:53:33.507 --> 01:53:35.261
You know, you weren't
this uptight in Boston.

2219
01:53:35.344 --> 01:53:36.757
-MARY: Oh.
-(Paul chuckles)

2220
01:53:36.840 --> 01:53:38.396
Danny, where do you stand
on indoor fireworks?

2221
01:53:38.479 --> 01:53:39.936
About as far away as I can.

2222
01:53:40.019 --> 01:53:41.432
-That's very wise.
-HOST: Ten, nine...

2223
01:53:41.515 --> 01:53:42.763
Oh, we're gonna miss it. Come on.

2224
01:53:42.846 --> 01:53:44.006
-Up on your feet.
-...eight, seven...

2225
01:53:44.089 --> 01:53:45.601
Up on your feet. Up on your feet.

2226
01:53:45.684 --> 01:53:48.175
-...six, five, four...
-Five, four...

2227
01:53:48.258 --> 01:53:51.145
PAUL, ANGUS and HOST: Three, two, one.

2228
01:53:51.228 --> 01:53:54.412
-Happy New Year!
-Happy New Year!

2229
01:53:54.495 --> 01:53:55.985
PAUL: Yes.

2230
01:53:56.068 --> 01:53:59.780
♪ Should old acquaintance be forgot... ♪

2231
01:53:59.863 --> 01:54:01.782
(Paul clears throat)

2232
01:54:01.865 --> 01:54:04.686
(quiet muttering)

2233
01:54:04.769 --> 01:54:06.490
Congratulations, Mr. Tully.

2234
01:54:06.573 --> 01:54:08.162
-Congratulations, Danny.
-Thank you.

2235
01:54:08.245 --> 01:54:09.867
Mary, congratulations.

2236
01:54:09.950 --> 01:54:12.100
Now, as I say, we're not
deploying this in here.

2237
01:54:12.183 --> 01:54:14.432
No. We're going to light
this sucker off in the kitchen.

2238
01:54:14.515 --> 01:54:15.697
-What?
-What?

2239
01:54:15.780 --> 01:54:17.105
-(Angus chuckles)
-All right. Come.

2240
01:54:17.188 --> 01:54:18.436
-Come, come, come.
-Come on, man.

2241
01:54:18.519 --> 01:54:19.976
-For real?
-This is coming with me.

2242
01:54:20.059 --> 01:54:24.981
♪ For auld lang syne ♪

2243
01:54:25.064 --> 01:54:26.675
♪ My dear ♪

2244
01:54:26.758 --> 01:54:32.054
♪ For auld lang syne. ♪

2245
01:54:32.137 --> 01:54:33.891
(explosion booms)

2246
01:54:33.974 --> 01:54:36.075
♪ ♪

2247
01:54:47.253 --> 01:54:49.286
(song ends)

2248
01:54:52.126 --> 01:54:55.160
("In Memory of Elizabeth Reed"
by Allman Brothers Band plays)

2249
01:55:02.928 --> 01:55:04.972
(indistinct chatter)

2250
01:55:06.437 --> 01:55:09.372
(laughter)

2251
01:55:22.981 --> 01:55:25.008
There's too much paprika.

2252
01:55:25.091 --> 01:55:26.768
Why'd you put in all that paprika?

2253
01:55:26.851 --> 01:55:28.407
Follow the recipe.

2254
01:55:28.490 --> 01:55:30.673
Now you have to add in
another cup of water.

2255
01:55:30.756 --> 01:55:32.626
What's wrong with you?

2256
01:55:34.564 --> 01:55:36.085
Come on, ladies!

2257
01:55:36.168 --> 01:55:38.236
(indistinct chatter)

2258
01:55:39.800 --> 01:55:41.420
STUDENT: Hey, Kountze.

2259
01:55:41.503 --> 01:55:43.422
Does... does it hurt?

2260
01:55:43.505 --> 01:55:45.061
Fuck yeah, it hurts.

2261
01:55:45.144 --> 01:55:47.426
Glare off the slopes, man,
burned me to a crisp.

2262
01:55:47.509 --> 01:55:48.966
(Angus laughs)

2263
01:55:49.049 --> 01:55:50.710
You think that's funny, Tully?

2264
01:55:51.713 --> 01:55:52.860
No, man.

2265
01:55:52.943 --> 01:55:54.972
Just glad you had a good vacation.

2266
01:55:55.055 --> 01:55:59.801
Welcome back, you snarling Visigoths.

2267
01:55:59.884 --> 01:56:03.475
I trust you all enjoyed
a refreshing holiday.

2268
01:56:03.558 --> 01:56:06.082
-Oh, hello, Mr. Kountze.
-(song fades)

2269
01:56:06.165 --> 01:56:08.150
Or should I say Icarus?

2270
01:56:08.233 --> 01:56:10.284
Fly a little too close to the sun, did we?

2271
01:56:10.367 --> 01:56:11.912
Huh?

2272
01:56:11.995 --> 01:56:13.155
Yeah.

2273
01:56:13.238 --> 01:56:14.585
Uh, all right.

2274
01:56:14.668 --> 01:56:16.587
Now, along with your skiing and swimming,

2275
01:56:16.670 --> 01:56:18.721
I hope you found time
to enlighten yourselves

2276
01:56:18.804 --> 01:56:21.889
about the Peloponnesian War
and its implications for today.

2277
01:56:21.972 --> 01:56:24.298
Just to check, we're going
to start with a short pop quiz

2278
01:56:24.381 --> 01:56:25.970
-on the reading...
-(students groaning)

2279
01:56:26.053 --> 01:56:27.895
...before we retake the final
from last semester.

2280
01:56:27.978 --> 01:56:30.238
<i>Omnia ex scrineis praeter stilum.</i>

2281
01:56:30.321 --> 01:56:32.257
(students groaning, murmuring)

2282
01:56:34.019 --> 01:56:36.888
♪ ♪

2283
01:56:52.114 --> 01:56:54.147
♪ ♪

2284
01:57:05.985 --> 01:57:07.655
Excuse me, Mr. Hunham?

2285
01:57:08.955 --> 01:57:10.938
Oh, Miss Crane.

2286
01:57:11.021 --> 01:57:13.809
Lydia. Uh, come in. Happy New Year.

2287
01:57:13.892 --> 01:57:16.020
Oh, same to you. Happy New Year.

2288
01:57:16.103 --> 01:57:17.615
Forgive me. I'm a clod.

2289
01:57:17.698 --> 01:57:19.353
I never called to thank you for inviting

2290
01:57:19.436 --> 01:57:20.948
the boy and me to your party.

2291
01:57:21.031 --> 01:57:22.026
And Mary.

2292
01:57:22.109 --> 01:57:23.225
It meant a lot.

2293
01:57:23.308 --> 01:57:24.655
Oh, you're so welcome.

2294
01:57:24.738 --> 01:57:26.195
It was fun.

2295
01:57:26.278 --> 01:57:29.198
Um, Dr. Woodrup is asking to see you.

2296
01:57:29.281 --> 01:57:30.727
He says it's urgent.

2297
01:57:30.810 --> 01:57:32.647
Oh.

2298
01:57:35.014 --> 01:57:37.091
(quiet chatter)

2299
01:57:44.925 --> 01:57:46.793
(knocking)

2300
01:58:02.613 --> 01:58:06.026
DR. WOODRUP: <i>Mr. Hunham, meet
Judy and Stanley Clotfelter.</i>

2301
01:58:06.109 --> 01:58:08.567
Angus Tully's mother and father.

2302
01:58:08.650 --> 01:58:10.404
-Stepfather.
-Hello.

2303
01:58:10.487 --> 01:58:12.208
Good morning.

2304
01:58:12.291 --> 01:58:14.078
They've brought something
very important to my attention.

2305
01:58:14.161 --> 01:58:15.673
STANLEY: We understand you took Angus

2306
01:58:15.756 --> 01:58:17.180
to Boston over the holidays.

2307
01:58:17.263 --> 01:58:19.006
I explained to Mr. Clotfelter

2308
01:58:19.089 --> 01:58:21.118
that you went on a field trip
for academic reasons.

2309
01:58:21.201 --> 01:58:22.350
That's right.

2310
01:58:22.433 --> 01:58:24.253
A field trip?

2311
